{
  "id": "carrier-24acc6-fan-motor",
  "brand": "Carrier",
  "model": "24ACC636A003",
  "equipment_type": "ac-condenser",
  "symptom": "Outdoor unit is running but the condenser fan is not spinning. Compressor is hot. High-side pressure is climbing above 450 PSI. Unit may trip on high-pressure cutout within a few minutes of starting.",
  "diagnosis": "Seized or burned-out condenser fan motor. Bearings failed \u2014 motor shaft won't turn by hand. Often caused by running the unit with debris restricting the fan blade or after a power surge.",
  "part_number": "HC39GE237 (Carrier 1/4 HP condenser fan motor, 1075 RPM, 208-230V)",
  "procedure": [
    "Kill power at the disconnect immediately \u2014 running the compressor without condenser airflow causes extreme high-side pressure and can damage the compressor.",
    "Try spinning the fan blade by hand (through the fan guard, carefully). If it won't turn or feels gritty, motor bearings are gone.",
    "Remove the fan guard (4 screws on Carrier 24ACC6). Lift it off with the blade still attached.",
    "Disconnect the motor leads from the contactor \u2014 typically a 3-wire connection (brown = hot, purple = capacitor, ground).",
    "Remove the motor mounting bolts (4 bolts through the motor bracket to the condenser top plate).",
    "Transfer the fan blade to the new motor: loosen the Allen set screw on the hub. Note the blade height \u2014 typically 1\" below the fan guard plane.",
    "Mount the new motor, reconnect leads. Verify the capacitor rating matches (typically 5 \u00b5F for 1/4 HP motor).",
    "Reinstall the fan guard. Hand-spin to check for clearance.",
    "Restore power. Verify fan starts when thermostat calls. Check motor amp draw \u2014 should be below 1.8A.",
    "Monitor high-side pressure \u2014 should drop to 300\u2013350 PSI range within 5 minutes."
  ],
  "safety_notes": [
    "High-side pressure above 450 PSI is dangerous \u2014 do not run the unit. Kill power immediately if you see this.",
    "The compressor may be extremely hot after running without fan \u2014 don't touch the discharge line.",
    "Fan blades can start unexpectedly if power is restored \u2014 always disconnect before working near the blade."
  ],
  "estimated_minutes": 40,
  "tags": [
    "fan motor",
    "condenser fan",
    "no fan spin",
    "high pressure",
    "carrier",
    "24ACC6",
    "seized motor",
    "hot compressor"
  ],
